        "title": "[codex] active-memory default to configured agents",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- Default Active Memory to configured OpenClaw agents when `plugins.entries.active-memory.config.agents` is omitted or empty.\n- Fall back to the implicit `main` agent for minimal configs that do not define `agents.list`.\n- Preserve explicit non-empty `config.agents` allowlist behavior.\n- Document the targeting contract in the Active Memory docs and plugin config help.\n\nThis matters because omitting `config.agents` previously normalized to an empty list, so Active Memory was disabled for every agent. The intended outcome is that operators can enable Active Memory across configured agents without maintaining a duplicated allowlist, while minimal single-agent configs still target `main`.\n\nOut of scope: changing chat type filtering, per-session toggles, memory indexing behavior, or the memory tools used by the Active Memory sub-agent.\n\nReview focus: whether the fallback to `agents.list[].id`, then implicit `main`, is the right default and whether explicit non-empty `config.agents` remains unchanged.\n\n## Linked context\n\nCloses #\n\nRelated #82528\n\nThis came from running OpenClaw with multiple Telegram topics routed to separate agents and needing Active Memory to apply consistently without copying the same agent list into plugin config.\n\n## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)\n\n- Behavior addressed:\n  Omitting `plugins.entries.active-memory.config.agents` normalized to an empty allowlist, so Active Memory skipped every agent instead of applying to configured agents.\n- Real environment tested:\n  OpenClaw 2026.6.5 on a Linux host with a systemd user gateway, Telegram group topics routed to `main`, `sementes`, `cloudfarm`, and `pedro-agenda`.\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch:\n  Applied the equivalent runtime change locally, removed `active-memory.config.agents`, restarted `openclaw-gateway`, then checked gateway status and memory search.\n- Evidence after fix:\n\n```text\nopenclaw gateway status --deep\nGateway version: 2026.6.5\nRuntime: running\nCapability: admin-capable\n```\n\n```text\njournalctl --user -u openclaw-gateway --since \"3 minutes ago\"\n[gateway] http server listening (12 plugins: active-memory, brave, browser, canvas, codex, device-pair, file-transfer, memory-core, openai, phone-control, talk-voice, telegram; 12.1s)\n```\n\n```text\nopenclaw memory search --query \"Pedro SeedSearch Markus\" --max-results 5\n0.545 memory/pendencias-grupo.md:1-21\n0.516 memory/2026-03-31.md:1-37\n0.453 memory/dreaming/light/2026-06-05.md:43-72\n```\n\n- Observed result after fix:\n  Active Memory no longer required a hardcoded `config.agents` list to apply across configured agents.\n- What was not tested:\n  A fresh live Telegram command round-trip was not captured on the final PR branch.\n- Proof limitations or environment constraints:\n  The production server was restored to upstream behavior after proof collection, using an explicit `config.agents` list until this PR is merged upstream.\n- Before evidence:\n  Reading the prior plugin implementation showed `normalizePluginConfig({}).agents` became `[]`, while `isEnabledForAgent` requires `config.agents.includes(agentId)`.\n\n## Tests and validation\n\nCommands run:\n\n```text\npnpm docs:list\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/active-memory/index.test.ts --maxWorkers=1\npnpm exec oxfmt --check extensions/active-memory/index.ts extensions/active-memory/index.test.ts\npnpm exec oxlint extensions/active-memory/index.ts extensions/active-memory/index.test.ts\nnode scripts/check-docs-mdx.mjs docs/concepts/active-memory.md\ngit diff --check upstream/main -- docs/concepts/active-memory.md extensions/active-memory/index.ts extensions/active-memory/index.test.ts extensions/active-memory/openclaw.plugin.json\n.agents/skills/autoreview/scripts/autoreview --mode commit --commit HEAD\n```\n\nRegression coverage added:\n\n- `defaults to all configured agents when no active-memory agent allowlist is set`\n- `defaults an empty active-memory agent allowlist to all configured agents`\n- `defaults to the implicit main agent when no agent list is configured`\n- `keeps an explicit active-memory agent allowlist`\n\nCI after the latest push:\n\n- GitHub PR checks passed with 0 failures on commit `fdf408d1e55464aced878f0fee85201324590de3` at latest polling.\n\n## Risk checklist\n\nDid user-visible behavior change? (`Yes`)\n\nDid config, environment, or migration behavior change? (`Yes`)\n\nDid security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? (`No`)\n\nHighest-risk area:\nOperators who intentionally omitted `config.agents` expecting Active Memory to run nowhere would now get Active Memory for configured agents, or `main` in minimal configs.\n\nRisk mitigation:\nExplicit non-empty `config.agents` still behaves as an allowlist. Operators can set `enabled: false`, disable the plugin entry, or provide a narrow `agents` list when they want less coverage. The docs and manifest help now state the omitted/empty default.\n\n## Current review state\n\nNext action:\nAwait maintainer review and CI completion.\n\nStill waiting on:\nGitHub PR checks for the latest push.\n\nBot/reviewer comments addressed:\nFilled in real behavior proof after the `triage: needs-real-behavior-proof` label was applied, then added docs/manifest alignment and focused regression coverage for omitted, empty, implicit-main, and explicit allowlist targeting.\n\n",
